# tmux-win

tmux-win is a native Windows port of tmux maintained at:

	https://github.com/Tienching/tmux-win

It keeps the tmux command model, configuration language, key tables, panes,
buffers, copy mode, jobs, popups, and client/server workflow, while replacing
the Unix-only runtime pieces with Win32 process, console, IPC, clipboard, and
path handling.

This project targets functional compatibility on Windows. It does not need to
ship on the same cadence or with the same packaging as Unix tmux; the release
bar is that the Windows build behaves like tmux for the features supported by
the Windows platform.

## Status

The Windows port builds as a native Win32 executable and uses ConPTY for pane
processes. The portable package is intended to run without MSYS2, Cygwin, WSL,
or a Unix compatibility runtime. MSYS2 is only a build toolchain.

Current Windows coverage includes:

- native server/client startup and command clients;
- detached sessions, windows, panes, layouts, zoom, resize, split, join, break,
  swap, rotate, respawn, and pane destruction;
- ConPTY-backed shell panes and command panes;
- run-shell, if-shell, pipe-pane, popup jobs, and process cleanup;
- copy mode, buffers, paste-buffer, save-buffer, load-buffer, and copy-pipe;
- Windows paths, current pane path discovery, and default config discovery;
- loopback IPC with endpoint-token authentication;
- Windows clipboard integration;
- command, option, and key-binding audits against Linux tmux when WSL and Linux
  tmux are available.

Detailed Windows notes are in:

- `windows/PORTING.md`
- `windows/VERIFY.md`
- `windows/RELEASE.md`
- `windows/PARITY-AUDIT.md`

## Requirements

Runtime:

- Windows 10 version 1809 or newer, or Windows 11;
- a console host with ConPTY support, such as Windows Terminal or the modern
  Windows console;
- PowerShell, cmd, or another Windows shell to launch `tmux.exe`.

Build:

- PowerShell 5 or newer;
- MSYS2 MinGW64 or UCRT64 GCC/G++;
- MSYS2 bison;
- MSYS2 pkgconf and libevent;
- MSYS2 binutils for portable package dependency collection.

A common local MSYS2 setup, run from an MSYS2 shell, is:

```powershell
pacman -S --needed `
  mingw-w64-x86_64-gcc `
  mingw-w64-x86_64-libevent `
  mingw-w64-x86_64-pkgconf `
  mingw-w64-x86_64-binutils `
  bison
```

If you use UCRT64, install the matching `mingw-w64-ucrt-x86_64-*` packages and
pass the matching compiler paths through `-CC` and `-CXX` when needed.

## Getting the Source

Clone this project:

```powershell
git clone git@github.com:Tienching/tmux-win.git
cd tmux-win
```

HTTPS clone:

```powershell
git clone https://github.com/Tienching/tmux-win.git
cd tmux-win
```

## Using a Portable Build

Unpack `tmux-win32-portable.zip` and run:

```powershell
.\tmux.exe -V
.\tmux.exe new-session
```

From a source checkout, install the portable package for the current Windows
user with:

```powershell
.\windows\install-portable.ps1 `
  -ZipPath .\dist\tmux-win32-portable.zip `
  -AddToUserPath `
  -Verify
```

The default install location is `%LOCALAPPDATA%\tmux`. The installer writes an
install marker and has a matching uninstall mode:

```powershell
.\windows\install-portable.ps1 -Uninstall
```

## Building from Source

From a PowerShell prompt at the repository root:

```powershell
.\windows\probe-mingw.ps1 -Yacc C:\msys64\usr\bin\bison.exe
.\windows\build-mingw.ps1 -Yacc C:\msys64\usr\bin\bison.exe
```

The build writes `tmux.exe` in the repository root by default.

To create a portable package:

```powershell
.\windows\package-mingw.ps1 `
  -Tmux .\tmux.exe `
  -Output .\dist\tmux-win32-portable `
  -ZipPath .\dist\tmux-win32-portable.zip `
  -Clean `
  -RunSmoke `
  -Zip
```

## Verification

Quick portable verification:

```powershell
.\windows\verify-portable.ps1 `
  -Tmux .\dist\tmux-win32-portable\tmux.exe
```

Direct runtime smoke:

```powershell
.\windows\smoke-runtime.ps1 `
  -Tmux .\tmux.exe `
  -TimeoutSeconds 180
```

Packaged runtime smoke:

```powershell
.\windows\smoke-runtime.ps1 `
  -Tmux .\dist\tmux-win32-portable\tmux.exe `
  -TimeoutSeconds 180
```

Full local release gate:

```powershell
.\windows\release-check.ps1 `
  -Yacc C:\msys64\usr\bin\bison.exe `
  -SmokeTimeoutSeconds 180 `
  -RespawnIterations 20 `
  -IpcAclIterations 5 `
  -JobStressIterations 20 `
  -ClientStressIterations 5 `
  -SignalMatrixIterations 3 `
  -StressIterations 2 `
  -SoakSeconds 20 `
  -ConsoleSoakSeconds 20 `
  -ClipboardStressIterations 10 `
  -RunConfigStress `
  -RunVisualTerminalVerify
```

Optional Linux comparison checks need WSL and Linux tmux:

```powershell
.\windows\linux-parity-matrix.ps1 `
  -WindowsTmux .\dist\tmux-win32-portable\tmux.exe `
  -Output .\dist\linux-parity-matrix.json

.\windows\linux-behavior-parity.ps1 `
  -WindowsTmux .\dist\tmux-win32-portable\tmux.exe `
  -Output .\dist\linux-behavior-parity.json
```

These checks compare the Windows binary against Linux tmux behavior and command
surface. They are evidence for functional compatibility; they are not a
requirement that Windows releases match Linux packaging or release timing.

## Release Artifacts

The release workflow produces:

- `dist\tmux-win32-portable`;
- `dist\tmux-win32-portable.zip`;
- `dist\tmux-win32-portable.zip.sha256`;
- `dist\release-check.json`;
- `dist\command-surface.json`;
- optional MSIX, signing, IPC boundary, hosted CI, source-state, Linux parity,
  and completion-audit summaries.

Use `windows/verify-release-artifacts.ps1` to cross-check an already produced
`dist` directory before publishing.

## Documentation

For tmux usage documentation, see the local `tmux.1` manpage. From an MSYS2 or
Unix-like shell:

```powershell
nroff -mdoc tmux.1 | less
```

The example configuration is in `example_tmux.conf`.

For Windows-specific verification and troubleshooting, start with
`windows/VERIFY.md`.

For debugging this Windows port, run tmux with `-v` or `-vv` to generate server
and client logs in the current directory. The Windows verification scripts also
write JSON or text summaries under `dist`.

## Contributing

File issues and pull requests in this repository:

	https://github.com/Tienching/tmux-win

Changes should include focused Windows verification when they touch process
lifecycle, ConPTY, IPC, clipboard, parser behavior, command surface, packaging,
or release scripts.

